There is a long tradition of sabotage by Russian intelligence services
There is no reason to suppose that the Russian Federation's Foreign Intelligence SVR or Military Intelligence GRU have abandoned this course of action.
In Soviet times, so-called DRG groups specialized in sabotage activities.
The name comes from the Russian words diversionno-razvedyvatelnaya gruppa: sabotage and reconnaissance group.
Western agents of the KGB, the Soviet security service, prepared detailed plans for important sabotage targets, says Vasily Mitrohin (1922-2004), an archivist who defected to the West.
His information was published in Christopher Andrew's books in the late 1990s and early 2000s
The targets included ports, shipyards, large dams, oil refineries and gas pipeline connections.
In Germany, the KGB provided DRG groups with uniforms and apparel for the Bundeswehr, railways, game wardens and road workers for covert operations.
This trick was used by Russian paratroopers in Crimea in February 2014: they donned local Ukrainian police riot gear, set up checkpoints on roads leading from the peninsula to Ukraine, and isolated Crimea from its mother country.
During the Cold War, agents hid supply packages containing mines, explosives, detonators and communications equipment in the terrain for sabotage groups.
As late as 1998, a KGB cache was found in Switzerland whose trap mine exploded when authorities sprayed it with a water cannon.
