Now let's go wrong - you no longer know whether to cry or laugh
Last Saturday, Karjalainen reported on a bill to amend the Animal Welfare Act.
The article gave the impression that the bill prohibits, in principle, the keeping of all animals that have not been specifically permitted by ministerial decrees as production animals, pets or otherwise related to business activities.
In other words, everything else is prohibited in principle, except for the animals specifically mentioned in the regulation.
If the bill ends up as law, it will probably mean that we are abandoning the general principle in Western democracies that the law specifically prohibits activities that endanger the security of society or good practice.
As a rule, legislation is now being enacted prohibiting all activities that are not specifically authorised by law or decree.
The change means that nothing new can be tried in business, for example, or anything else can be done until the law or decree approving it has been passed.
The Government's performance in legislative drafting in general has been weak.
If we now start on the path that, in principle, everything is forbidden in Finland, which is not specifically allowed, we no longer know whether to cry or laugh.
I have no doubt that the Animal Welfare Act needs updating.
But a legislative project along these lines has no place in democracy.
Unfortunately, I am not very familiar with the Constitution, but I wonder whether it will accept this 'everything is forbidden, which is not expressly permitted by law or regulation' procedure.
Hopefully, there will be some sensible minister who will halt the progress of such a legislative project.
