What makes a person popular, charismatic or admired?
Researchers at the University of Sydney who have analysed the matter have outlined two types of "coolness" consisting of slightly different traits: the generally attractive coolness and the partly opposite dissident coolness.
Attractively cool people, according to the researchers' description, had many traits considered socially desirable: they were outgoing, friendly, amiable, and competent.
Dissidents, on the other hand, were characterized by distance, independence, rebellion and edge.
They were hungry for experience and paid little attention to outside judgments.
Both types shared good self-esteem and a stable emotional life.
The role of Kovis is not cool in the long run: a high status in adolescence does not necessarily lead to success later in life.
