Billionaire Elon Musk quits Tesla as chairman of the board – $20 million fined for tweets
Elon Musk, founder of space rocket and electric car companies, is avoiding fraud charges through a deal with the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission.
Billionaire Elon Musk quits his position as chairman of the board of electric car company Tesla and agrees to a $20 million fine.
Musk is stepping down as part of an agreement he made with the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission.
By agreeing, Musk avoids fraud charges.
Musk was threatened with securities fraud by the SEC over tweets he sent in August.
In them, Musk wrote that he was preparing to pull electric car company Tesla off the stock exchange, which caused the company's stock price to skyrocket.
Under the agreement, Musk will not be allowed to serve as chairman of Tesla's board of directors for three years.
In addition, Tesla must appoint a new "independent member" to its board of directors and include two "independent directors" on its management team.
Tesla must also set up a committee to oversee Musk's communications.
Musk will continue as CEO of Tesla.
In addition to Musk's personal $20 million fine, the Tesla company will also have to pay the equivalent of $20 million in fines to the financial regulator.
Tweets misled investors
According to the SEC, Musk's tweets misled investors and Tesla shareholders.
Musk claimed that he had secured financing to buy Tesla off the exchange back into a private limited liability company.
According to the billionaire's tweets, the company would have been bought off the stock exchange for $420 per share.
Tesla's stock price rose more than ten percent in a day after the tweets, but later fell.
According to the SEC, Musk's claims had no basis whatsoever.
According to the supervisor, he had not actually negotiated the funding he claimed.
Nor had he discussed the withdrawal from the stock exchange with the rest of the management team or the company's board of directors.
On Friday of this week, the rate fell 14% after the SEC announced a fraud charge.
The news of the agreement is expected to confirm the company's share price again.
